<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-vector-spaces" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Vector Spaces</title>

  <p>
In <xref ref="thm-vec-prop"/> we identified eight properties satisfied by vector addition
and scalar multiplication on <m>{\mathbb R}^n</m>. It turns out that these properties are
exactly what is needed to produce the more general notion of a vector space.
</p>

 <definition xml:id="def-vec-spaces">
  <statement>
  <p>
  A <term>vector space <m>V</m> over <m>\mathbb R</m></term> is a set <m>V</m> together with
  <ul>
  <li>
  <p> an operation <m>+</m> satisfying 
  <m>\vect{u},\vect{v}\in V\implies \vect{u}+\vect{v}\in V</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p> a scalar multiplication of <m>\mathbb R</m> satisfying 
  <m>\vect{u}\in V,\, c\in\mathbb R\implies c\vect{u}\in V</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p> a vector <m>\vect{0}\in V</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p> for each <m>\vect{u}\in V</m> a vector <m>-\vect{u}\in V</m>
  </p>
  </li>
</ul>
satisfying, for all <m>\vect{u}, \vect{v}, \vect{w} \in V</m> and <m>c, d \in \R</m>,
  <ol>
  <li>
  <p><m>\vect{u} + \vect{v} = \vect{v} + \vect{u}\quad</m> (commutativity)
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>(\vect{u} + \vect{v}) + \vect{w} = \vect{u} + (\vect{v}+ \vect{w})\quad</m> 
  (associativity)
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>\vect{u} + \vect{0} = \vect{u}</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>\vect{u} + (-\vect{u}) = \vect{0}</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>c(\vect{u} + \vect{v}) = c\vect{u} + c\vect{v}\quad</m> (distributivity)
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>(c+d)\vect{u} = c\vect{u} + d\vect{u}\quad</m> (distributivity)
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>c(d\vect{u}) = (cd)\vect{u}</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>1\vect{u} = \vect{u}</m>.</p>
  </li>
  </ol></p>
  </statement>
  </definition>

<remark xml:id="rem-vec-space-terms">
<statement>
<p>
We call the <m>+</m> operation <term>addition</term>. When addition satisfies 
<m>\vect{u},\vect{v}\in V\implies \vect{u}+\vect{v}\in V</m> 
(the first dot point above), we say that <m>V</m> <term>is closed under addition</term>. 
Similarly, when the scalar multiplication operation satisfies 
<m>\vect{u}\in V,\, c\in\mathbb R\implies c\vect{u}\in V</m>, we say that <m>V</m> is 
<term>closed under scalar multiplication</term>. 
</p>

<p>
The vector <m>\vect{0}</m> is called a <term>zero vector</term>, and 
given <m>\vect{u}\in V</m>, the vector <m>-\vect{u}</m> is called an 
<term>additive inverse of</term> <m>\vect{u}</m>. (In the first tutorial you will be
asked to show that the zero vector and the additive inverses are unique.)
</p>
</statement>
</remark>

<remark xml:id="rem-general-vec-space">
<statement>
<p>
We have not given the most general definition of a vector space. To do this, we would need
to replace the real numbers <m>\mathbb R</m> by a more general mathematical object
called a <term>field</term>. You will learn more about fields in second-year mathematics.
</p>
</statement>
</remark>

<example xml:id="ex-Rn-is-vec-space">
<statement>
<p>
By <xref ref="thm-vec-prop"/> we know that <m>{\mathbb R}^n</m> under the usual addition 
and scalar multiplication operations is a vector space.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-other-vec-spaces">
<statement>
<p>
Here are some other examples of vector spaces. We will leave the proofs as an exercise 
(some of which are difficult!).
<ul>
  <li>
  <p> The set of all functions <m>f\colon \mathbb R\to\mathbb R</m> under the usual pointwise 
  addition and scalar multiplication operations is a vector space over <m>\mathbb R</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p> The sets 
  <md>
<mrow>
\amp P_n(\mathbb R)=\{\text{polynomials } a_0+a_1x+\dots+a_nx^n:a_i\in\mathbb R\}\\
\amp C(\mathbb R)=\{\text{continuously functions } \mathbb R\to\mathbb R\}\\
\amp C^1(\mathbb{R})=\{\text{continuously differentiable functions } \mathbb R\to\mathbb R\}
</mrow>
</md>
  are all vector spaces over <m>\mathbb R</m> under the usual pointwise operations.
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  We will later see that the set of <m>m\times n</m> with real entries is a vector space
  over <m>\mathbb R</m> under the usual operations of matrix addition and scalar
  multiplication.
  </li>
</ul>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

</section>